Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high. Mince @garlic{2%cloves}. Finely chop @spinach{5%ounce} until you have 2 cups of very packed spinach. Cut @lemon{1} in half; cut one half into wedges. Cut @grape tomatoes{8%ounce} in half. Remove @Italian chicken sausage{12%ounce} from casings of 4 links (use the others as you like). Pick @parsley{¼%ounce} leaves from stems and finely chop; discard stems.

> Pasta night just got so easy, it's ridiculous. Everything in this recipe (and we really mean everything) comes together in a single pan.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, tall-sided pan over medium-high heat (use an ovenproof pan if you have one). Add sausage, breaking up meat into pieces. Cook until just browned, about ~{3%minutes}.

Add tomatoes and garlic to pan with sausage. Cook, stirring occasionally, until tomatoes start to wilt, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add @orzo pasta{1⅓%cup} (we sent more) and @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until orzo is coated in juices, ~{1%minute}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Since the orzo is cooked risotto-style, with the minimal amount of water it needs to get al dente, you don't even have to drain it.

Add @water{4%cups}, @chicken stock concentrate{2}, and a pinch of salt to same pan. Bring to a boil, then lower heat to medium. Let simmer, stirring occasionally, until orzo is almost al dente, ~{7-9%minutes}. Stir in spinach and cook until wilted, about ~{3%minutes} more.

> TIP: If mixture seems dry, add water ¼ cup at a time until loosened.

Stir @mozzarella cheese{½%cup} and a squeeze of lemon into pan. Season with salt, pepper, and more lemon (to taste).

> TIP: If your pan is not ovenproof, transfer mixture to a #baking dish{} at this point.

Sprinkle @panko breadcrumbs{½%cup} and @Parmesan cheese{½%can} over top of orzotto. Broil until panko is golden brown, ~{1-3%minutes}.

Divide orzotto between plates. Sprinkle parsley over top. Serve with lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over.